Line Wobbler, which is why I'm here.

128
00:06:33,841 --> 00:06:36,342
So I'm going to talk about what inspired me to make the

129
00:06:36,362 --> 00:06:41,004
game, and then how I iterated it towards a proper art

130
00:06:41,064 --> 00:06:41,805
piece, in a way.

131
00:06:43,233 --> 00:06:48,776
So first the game was made at the Exile Game Jam, which is a small game jam in Denmark.

132
00:06:48,956 --> 00:06:50,697
And it's a very nice setting.

133
00:06:50,837 --> 00:06:54,158
And I made it to there, teamed up with Matthias Maschek.

134
00:06:55,299 --> 00:06:58,260
So we kind of together kind of brainstormed on different things.

135
00:06:58,641 --> 00:07:02,463
So I was looking at springs, and Matthias was looking at LED strips.

136
00:07:02,863 --> 00:07:07,925
And I got the idea to look at springs just before the jam by doing research online.

137
00:07:08,105 --> 00:07:11,727
And as you know, you look at cat videos when you do research online.

138
00:07:12,027 --> 00:07:16,053
So this is the actual literal inspiration for the controller of Line Wobbler.

139
00:07:19,915 --> 00:07:20,675
So this is a cat.

140
00:07:20,735 --> 00:07:22,456
Apparently, it's not my cat, unfortunately.

141
00:07:22,777 --> 00:07:27,019
But fortunately, I guess, because it does that every morning at 5 o'clock,

142
00:07:27,059 --> 00:07:27,499
apparently.

143
00:07:29,160 --> 00:07:30,841
But I thought, like, you know, the cat has so much fun.

144
00:07:30,902 --> 00:07:32,542
So I want to make a controller that has, like,

145
00:07:32,583 --> 00:07:34,203
this kind of cool vibrating feedback.

146
00:07:34,904 --> 00:07:38,326
And so humans should enjoy this kind of interaction as well.

147
00:07:38,366 --> 00:07:43,689
So it took me a while to figure out how to measure the movement of the spring.

148
00:07:44,730 --> 00:07:47,132
So at first I thought it could be bend sensors,

149
00:07:47,612 --> 00:07:49,814
or it could be like a little joystick on the base.

150
00:07:50,595 --> 00:07:52,536
But finally arrived at accelerometers.

151
00:07:53,857 --> 00:07:58,221
And so I figured out how to kind of use the spring.

152
00:07:58,901 --> 00:08:03,385
And at the jam, Matthias was working with the LED strip.

153
00:08:03,645 --> 00:08:06,688
And so it was a very kind of mechanics-driven design process.

154
00:08:06,708 --> 00:08:09,730
So mechanics in this case, I mean like literal mechanics,

155
00:08:09,810 --> 00:08:14,014
like physical objects that kind of define what the game will be.

156
00:08:14,514 --> 00:08:20,137
So what we wanted to do is we want to build a game entirely based on these two objects only.

157
00:08:20,217 --> 00:08:24,420
So no buttons, nothing else, just the one-dimensional display and a spring.

158
00:08:26,401 --> 00:08:33,404
So this limitation to this simple interaction meant that we were quite limited in what we could do.

159
00:08:33,965 --> 00:08:36,406
So obviously you can bend a spring back and forth.

160
00:08:36,706 --> 00:08:39,608
So that kind of works just like a normal joystick in a way.

161
00:08:39,908 --> 00:08:41,849
But you also got this additional interaction of

162
00:08:41,909 --> 00:08:43,410
kind of flinging the spring.

163
00:08:44,071 --> 00:08:46,632
So it's a new thing.

164
00:08:46,732 --> 00:08:50,995
And once we tested this, so we had a debug output on the LED

165
00:08:51,015 --> 00:08:52,916
strip, just like the spring position.

166
00:08:53,276 --> 00:08:55,417
And once we flung it back and forth, it's like, oh, this

167
00:08:55,437 --> 00:08:57,859
looks kind of violent, this movement.

168
00:08:57,899 --> 00:09:00,560
So why don't we say this is an attack, and we add some

169
00:09:00,640 --> 00:09:01,221
enemies to it?

170
00:09:01,641 --> 00:09:05,184
So that kind of kick-started the idea for Line Warbler basically.

171
00:09:05,264 --> 00:09:10,128
It went from there, so it said, OK, if we can move along the spring, what else can there be?

172
00:09:10,168 --> 00:09:12,910
So there could be a timing challenge where you have to wait, and then you have to go,

173
00:09:13,190 --> 00:09:14,331
and you get pushed in one direction.

174
00:09:16,352 --> 00:09:18,314
That is basically all the game is.

175
00:09:19,115 --> 00:09:22,978
So there's not much more to it, I mean, from a mechanics perspective.

176
00:09:23,718 --> 00:09:27,240
And yeah, so once I put these little accelerometers in here,

177
00:09:27,260 --> 00:09:30,562
they're actually behind this, inside this little 3D printed knob here.

178
00:09:31,242 --> 00:09:33,623
And they work way better than expected.

179
00:09:33,663 --> 00:09:35,364
So the accuracy is much, much higher.

180
00:09:35,384 --> 00:09:37,785
I thought I could maybe detect if it's forward or backwards,

181
00:09:38,306 --> 00:09:40,187
but it's actually a very precise joystick.

182
00:09:40,247 --> 00:09:42,548
So that allowed me to push up the skill ceiling

183
00:09:42,568 --> 00:09:44,969
by making the game much faster and thus a bit harder.

184
00:09:45,009 --> 00:09:46,970
So it's kind of a very difficult game,

185
00:09:47,090 --> 00:09:49,592
but I can kind of make the levels easier to compensate.

186
00:09:52,220 --> 00:10:00,442
So over to the graphics. Because it's an LED strip, it's only one line of light, you don't really have much depth of information to convey to the player.

187
00:10:00,522 --> 00:10:05,503
So there's no sprites, there's no text, you know, there's barely any information besides color.

188
00:10:05,943 --> 00:10:12,545
And so I decided to stick to, we decided to stick to a very limited set of information we could convey.

189
00:10:12,585 --> 00:10:17,646
So it's very much like a traffic light in a way. So green is good, red is bad, and orange is somewhere in the middle.

190
00:10:18,006 --> 00:10:20,686
So that's kind of what we used. And that also kind of...

191
00:10:21,527 --> 00:10:24,010
prevents me in a way from kind of expanding the game

192
00:10:24,851 --> 00:10:26,813
to make it deeper because like now when I add

193
00:10:27,193 --> 00:10:28,655
some teleporters or some pickups,

194
00:10:29,016 --> 00:10:30,097
then the question becomes, you know,

195
00:10:30,117 --> 00:10:32,019
what does this weird blue purple thing mean?

196
00:10:32,159 --> 00:10:33,681
And that is not quite as obvious.

197
00:10:33,741 --> 00:10:36,344
And it might make sense as a kind of a hardcore mode

198
00:10:36,424 --> 00:10:37,665
or like an advanced mode where people

199
00:10:38,166 --> 00:10:41,789
want to discover what they're doing, but I found like showing this game, because it is

200
00:10:41,829 --> 00:10:44,111
so simple, also non-gamers play it.

201
00:10:44,191 --> 00:10:48,935
And surprisingly, or I don't know, for me surprisingly, they're not willing to explore.

202
00:10:49,055 --> 00:10:51,938
So when they see something they don't understand, they just stop.

203
00:10:52,598 --> 00:10:57,542
And so then, you know, you need to have some kind of way to convey what they're doing.

204
00:10:58,783 --> 00:11:03,866
I actually was forced to cut this, well not forced, but like with this little short instruction

205
00:11:03,886 --> 00:11:08,728
sheet that you can kind of see on the screen there, that was necessary to have people understand,

206
00:11:09,048 --> 00:11:11,429
you know, oh this is lava, you shouldn't go there when it's bright.

207
00:11:11,449 --> 00:11:18,193
I mean you could, you know, as gamers we figure that out, but like normal players or people

208
00:11:18,213 --> 00:11:21,494
that are not as exposed to video games, they don't have this kind of...

209
00:11:23,195 --> 00:11:28,316
It's an interesting balance you need to find there.

210
00:11:30,577 --> 00:11:33,957
Also the LED strips are really cool because they're extremely bright.

211
00:11:34,397 --> 00:11:37,758
So whenever I work on them, I kind of see these little dots afterwards in my vision

212
00:11:37,798 --> 00:11:39,458
for hours almost.

213
00:11:39,859 --> 00:11:44,400
So they're painfully bright, but I kind of decided to use that to my advantage to kind

214
00:11:44,440 --> 00:11:44,480
of...

215
00:11:45,420 --> 00:11:47,381
not quite torture the player, but kind of really,

216
00:11:48,381 --> 00:11:51,922
when things happen in the game, you kind of, you flash them a bit.

217
00:11:51,942 --> 00:11:53,503
So it reminded me a bit of asteroids.

218
00:11:53,523 --> 00:11:56,224
I don't know if any of you have played this in the vector graphics display.

219
00:11:56,244 --> 00:11:57,944
It was like, how bright this looked, and it was so cool.

220
00:11:57,964 --> 00:11:59,505
Wow, how can a TV look that bright?

221
00:11:59,905 --> 00:12:01,606
And so I kind of wanted to capture that feeling as well.

222
00:12:01,666 --> 00:12:04,867
So all the main objects of the game have like full brightness, and

223
00:12:04,887 --> 00:12:08,308
then the rest of the game is kind of a very mellow color.

224
00:12:09,709 --> 00:12:10,969
And also when you kill enemies,

225
00:12:11,210 --> 00:12:13,311
I'm not going to show it now,

226
00:12:14,492 --> 00:12:16,293
then the entire screen flashes in full brightness,

227
00:12:16,313 --> 00:12:18,034
but it's very fast because the frame rate is so high,

228
00:12:18,054 --> 00:12:19,555
so it's almost subconscious.

229
00:12:20,135 --> 00:12:21,776
And this high frame rate also helped me

230
00:12:21,997 --> 00:12:24,398
to kind of make the game look really buttery smooth.

231
00:12:25,018 --> 00:12:28,701
and together with the low latency of this accelerometer,

232
00:12:29,021 --> 00:12:31,803
I get a really immediate feedback of what the player is doing.

233
00:12:31,823 --> 00:12:36,106
And that, I think, helped also make the game feel so nice.

234
00:12:36,146 --> 00:12:38,307
Because I think in a lot of modern games,

235
00:12:38,727 --> 00:12:40,448
there's a trend to higher and higher latency,

236
00:12:40,789 --> 00:12:42,350
especially like mobile phones, when you tap it,

237
00:12:42,370 --> 00:12:45,011
there's a built-in latency of, I think, 50 milliseconds at least.

238
00:12:45,472 --> 00:12:47,596
And it goes up with certain devices.

239
00:12:47,996 --> 00:12:50,560
So it's like this immediacy is going away.

240
00:12:50,821 --> 00:12:54,347
And I wanted to recapture that in this custom hardware game.

241
00:12:54,367 --> 00:12:57,252
