But more the community that we have access to.

701
00:40:03,261 --> 00:40:06,322
So just in our one makerspace in central London.

702
00:40:07,042 --> 00:40:10,524
There are four or five different companies that have kick-started in the last six months

703
00:40:10,644 --> 00:40:14,307
and between them raised well over a million pounds in kick-start revenue.

704
00:40:14,347 --> 00:40:19,790
So everyone is sharing ideas, information, mailing lists, all of this stuff.

705
00:40:19,931 --> 00:40:24,233
And emotional support, like everyone knows, if it's day 27 of your kick-starter,

706
00:40:24,253 --> 00:40:28,136
that you're in a very particular emotional place and you need shoulder rubs and pizza

707
00:40:28,376 --> 00:40:31,658
and just kind of pushing through the last few days of your campaign.

708
00:40:32,219 --> 00:40:34,821
And yeah, find those communities because they're incredible.

709
00:40:36,764 --> 00:40:38,285
So then there's your supply chain.

710
00:40:38,385 --> 00:40:42,666
So what we did is we went out to China and we found Chinese manufacturing partners.

711
00:40:43,027 --> 00:40:44,387
We did not try to do that alone.

712
00:40:44,767 --> 00:40:47,988
There are lots and lots of different knowledge networks that you can tap into

713
00:40:48,288 --> 00:40:51,409
that are going to help you find the right manufacturing partner in China.

714
00:40:51,750 --> 00:40:53,490
That partner exists for everybody,

715
00:40:53,770 --> 00:40:57,271
but there are very, very, very, very many different ways of getting it done.

716
00:40:57,752 --> 00:41:00,033
So we found a sourcing company that actually sort of

717
00:41:00,413 --> 00:41:02,734
transacts with and manages our supply chain,

718
00:41:03,135 --> 00:41:04,996
and we found them through Hardware Club,

719
00:41:05,016 --> 00:41:07,277
which is a members-only community of startups

720
00:41:07,297 --> 00:41:08,718
who are doing hardware all around the world.

721
00:41:09,438 --> 00:41:12,442
You then need to deal with getting it from the factory to people.

722
00:41:12,862 --> 00:41:16,567
So there are a whole bunch of third-party logistics companies that you can use.

723
00:41:16,967 --> 00:41:21,392
We're currently using Shipwire, which is really great for e-commerce and Kickstarter,

724
00:41:21,452 --> 00:41:23,315
not so great for shipping into retail.

725
00:41:23,735 --> 00:41:25,157
And then you need to deal with customer service,

726
00:41:25,217 --> 00:41:29,102
but then you can use something like Zendesk to help you automate and manage that process.

727
00:41:30,756 --> 00:41:33,398
We talked a bit already about launch in e-commerce through Kickstarter.

728
00:41:33,438 --> 00:41:37,721
It's incredibly important for revenues and also for kind of awareness and marketing.

729
00:41:38,741 --> 00:41:42,284
If you successfully kickstart your project, you have a good chance of getting onto Amazon

730
00:41:42,324 --> 00:41:48,407
Launchpad, which is a kind of startups-only program where you get a whole bunch of free

731
00:41:48,467 --> 00:41:51,689
additional services delivered to you by Amazon that you would normally have to pay a bunch

732
00:41:51,709 --> 00:41:56,072
of money for, like putting that video that is on our Amazon product page.

733
00:41:56,472 --> 00:41:59,114
Normally, you have to pay thousands of dollars for that, and we get it for free.

734
00:42:00,963 --> 00:42:09,793
And finally, the stuff that I don't need to tell you guys about, because if you're an indie game developer, you're already doing this really well, MailChimp, you know, all of these different sort of promotional tools that you've already got.

735
00:42:10,333 --> 00:42:17,161
And one thing I would say is, I think Robin and I both found this, that if you have a really weird, interesting indie hardware game,

736
00:42:17,581 --> 00:42:19,902
you have a much better chance of getting good coverage

737
00:42:20,162 --> 00:42:21,143
because it's so different.

738
00:42:21,383 --> 00:42:25,445
And, you know, we haven't yet paid any YouTube content creators

739
00:42:25,485 --> 00:42:27,546
for any of the coverage that we've had to date.

740
00:42:27,946 --> 00:42:29,627
And I think that's largely a function of,

741
00:42:30,087 --> 00:42:30,988
they look at it, they think,

742
00:42:31,048 --> 00:42:32,448
that is sufficiently weird and interesting

743
00:42:32,488 --> 00:42:33,329
that I just want to try it.

744
00:42:33,389 --> 00:42:34,129
And if I'm going to try it,

745
00:42:34,189 --> 00:42:35,930
I may as well make a video out of it.

746
00:42:36,530 --> 00:42:37,651
And that makes a big difference

747
00:42:37,671 --> 00:42:38,731
when you're trying to get started.

748
00:42:39,940 --> 00:42:45,542
So, super quickly, Kickstarter, a ton of things we got right,

749
00:42:45,962 --> 00:42:47,522
obviously a whole bunch of things we got wrong,

750
00:42:48,602 --> 00:42:50,303
so many things I could say about Kickstarter,

751
00:42:50,323 --> 00:42:52,363
but here's my one big takeaway for you all.

752
00:42:52,863 --> 00:42:55,184
Your pricing is more important than your marketing.

753
00:42:55,924 --> 00:42:57,744
Our early bird pricing jumped by $10,

754
00:42:57,884 --> 00:43:01,905
and it was after we'd raised about a third of our target,

755
00:43:02,506 --> 00:43:05,886
and basically the person 501 who came to our site

756
00:43:06,046 --> 00:43:07,467
had to pay $10 more than person 500,

757
00:43:07,767 --> 00:43:09,647
and that just pissed people off.

758
00:43:10,228 --> 00:43:15,452
So they didn't, and our numbers dropped really badly in a kind of scary way.

759
00:43:15,552 --> 00:43:20,035
So, like, there's a ton of knowledge out there about how to do physical Kickstarters right.

760
00:43:20,075 --> 00:43:23,278
Look at the board game community, especially a guy called Jamie Stegmeyer,

761
00:43:23,618 --> 00:43:29,242
who's super expert in kind of, and has shared very kind of much information on that.

762
00:43:31,018 --> 00:43:36,022
Okay, so one more thing for us about how manufacturing works and how profitability works.

763
00:43:36,582 --> 00:43:40,265
So it's a very different world if you're coming from indie software to indie hardware.

764
00:43:40,665 --> 00:43:42,947
You're used to Apple or Steam taking kind of 30%.

765
00:43:43,007 --> 00:43:47,691
There's a whole bunch of different people who are going to take money from you in a

766
00:43:47,771 --> 00:43:49,092
whole bunch of different ways.

767
00:43:50,453 --> 00:43:53,315
And you kind of have to be alert to what all of these mean.

768
00:43:54,075 --> 00:44:01,058
So, when you're thinking about that $99 that our game costs if you go buy it in Marbles

769
00:44:01,098 --> 00:44:05,239
the Brain store around the corner, firstly the retailers are going to take a chunk.

770
00:44:05,800 --> 00:44:08,381
And that chunk varies massively depending on what channel.

771
00:44:08,561 --> 00:44:10,741
So if you're on Kickstarter, they're going to take about 5%.

772
00:44:10,881 --> 00:44:17,104
If you're like a startup doing a deal with a niche retailer who's going to help you

773
00:44:17,124 --> 00:44:18,764
launch your product, they might take as much as 60%.

774
00:44:20,401 --> 00:44:24,554
Um, that channel also varies depending on which, um...

775
00:44:26,096 --> 00:44:26,756
category you're in.

776
00:44:27,156 --> 00:44:29,277
So if you're in what's kind of STEM and electronics,

777
00:44:29,657 --> 00:44:31,658
they're much more used even in big department stores

778
00:44:31,678 --> 00:44:33,219
to thinking about 20 to 30%.

779
00:44:33,999 --> 00:44:35,440
But if you're in toys and games,

780
00:44:35,880 --> 00:44:38,461
then they're used to cards against humanity type products

781
00:44:38,521 --> 00:44:40,342
where it doesn't cost them hardly anything to make

782
00:44:40,682 --> 00:44:42,943
and you can take a much, much bigger slice of the pie

783
00:44:42,983 --> 00:44:43,743
if you're the retailer.

784
00:44:44,123 --> 00:44:45,884
So actually like figuring out where your product

785
00:44:45,924 --> 00:44:48,945
is gonna sit in retail and knowing how the kind of margin

786
00:44:48,985 --> 00:44:50,005
and buying structure works

787
00:44:50,065 --> 00:44:51,226
is actually a really important thing.

788
00:44:52,036 --> 00:44:53,756
So on the other side of it, you have your COGS,

789
00:44:53,856 --> 00:44:55,177
or cost of goods sold.

790
00:44:55,537 --> 00:44:57,177
So that's basically everything that it costs

791
00:44:57,217 --> 00:44:58,637
to make one copy of the game,

792
00:44:58,998 --> 00:45:00,838
plus everything it costs to get to a warehouse

793
00:45:01,278 --> 00:45:02,658
in the country where you're gonna be selling it.

794
00:45:03,098 --> 00:45:04,959
So also kind of container shipping,

795
00:45:05,379 --> 00:45:08,120
import charges, other crap.

796
00:45:09,460 --> 00:45:10,840
And then if you're kind of,

797
00:45:10,980 --> 00:45:13,341
there's the actually warehouse to retailer

798
00:45:13,361 --> 00:45:14,921
or warehouse to customer kind of bit,

799
00:45:14,961 --> 00:45:15,361
which is another 5%.

800
00:45:15,821 --> 00:45:18,802
The mathematically savvy of you will have noticed

801
00:45:18,842 --> 00:45:20,402
that if you add up all of those costs,

802
00:45:20,422 --> 00:45:21,683
you can end up making no money.

803
00:45:22,644 --> 00:45:24,066
on your own retail product.

804
00:45:24,087 --> 00:45:25,930
And that is possible, really possible.

805
00:45:26,471 --> 00:45:28,574
And you can underestimate these things very easily.

806
00:45:29,035 --> 00:45:32,301
So, like, we knew pretty much.

807
00:45:33,443 --> 00:45:36,385
where we thought we were going to end up before we did our Kickstarter campaign,

808
00:45:36,405 --> 00:45:39,707
and we kind of planned all of our sort of pricing and everything around that.

809
00:45:40,167 --> 00:45:44,610
Because if you don't, you can end up with all sorts of troubles down the line.

810
00:45:44,650 --> 00:45:47,812
So you have to be very, very kind of thoughtful ahead of time about this.

811
00:45:47,832 --> 00:45:50,954
You're going to have to work with those manufacturing partners.

812
00:45:50,974 --> 00:45:53,075
You're not going to be able to get to this number on your own.

813
00:45:53,095 --> 00:45:55,356
You're going to have to talk to people in China who are going to have to...

814
00:45:55,777 --> 00:45:59,298
It helps decide what components you're going to use, all of these sorts of things.

815
00:45:59,818 --> 00:46:05,301
To give you a quick example of how that looks, like in the sharp end of design, this is our

816
00:46:05,561 --> 00:46:10,103
engineer Chris Shaw's patented custom in-house frictional coefficient bug fixing test.

817
00:46:11,323 --> 00:46:16,125
Yep, it's an angle and a bit of plastic, and down to the right you can see a shiny

818
00:46:16,145 --> 00:46:17,386
bit of plastic that has fallen off.

819
00:46:19,220 --> 00:46:21,161
So, if you've got a stacking game,

820
00:46:21,541 --> 00:46:23,421
one of the most important things about a stacking game

821
00:46:23,441 --> 00:46:24,502
is that your pieces can stack.

822
00:46:25,722 --> 00:46:28,623
Our 3D printed prototypes and our epoxy resin

823
00:46:28,743 --> 00:46:31,043
kind of next kinds of prototypes

824
00:46:31,363 --> 00:46:33,224
had a very sticky kind of finish,

825
00:46:33,324 --> 00:46:35,084
either through paint or through the kinds of materials

826
00:46:35,104 --> 00:46:35,584
that we were using.

827
00:46:35,964 --> 00:46:37,645
And that meant that when you kind of built a tower out of them,

828
00:46:37,685 --> 00:46:39,305
even if that tower was slightly janky,

829
00:46:39,565 --> 00:46:41,426
they would all kind of just hold in place.

830
00:46:42,206 --> 00:46:43,806
And that was really good,

831
00:46:44,006 --> 00:46:45,767
because it meant that you would sometimes stack a piece

832
00:46:45,787 --> 00:46:47,007
and be convinced that it would fall off,

833
00:46:47,027 --> 00:46:48,307
when it didn't and you felt good.

834
00:46:49,047 --> 00:46:54,570
With the pure ABS, so these are the first shots that came out of our injection molding tool.

835
00:46:55,050 --> 00:47:00,032
They were slippy as hell. There was nothing. If they weren't exactly parallel all the way up,

836
00:47:00,573 --> 00:47:04,714
the tower would just kind of explode without warning, which is not good.

837
00:47:05,915 --> 00:47:09,958
So instead, what we did was look for different solutions to that.

838
00:47:10,218 --> 00:47:12,060
There were two different ways we could solve the problem.

839
00:47:12,080 --> 00:47:14,001
The way that we thought we were going to solve the problem

840
00:47:14,442 --> 00:47:16,203
is by etching the molding tool.

841
00:47:16,283 --> 00:47:19,646
So this is basically a process where you apply some kind of texture

842
00:47:20,066 --> 00:47:21,327
to the stainless steel tool,

843
00:47:21,647 --> 00:47:24,369
so that when you shoot the plastic into it, that texture kind of gets on.

844
00:47:24,389 --> 00:47:28,633
So if you think about like a walnut veneer dashboard in a car or something like that,

845
00:47:28,653 --> 00:47:29,513
it has that kind of texture.

846
00:47:29,954 --> 00:47:31,074
That actually made it worse,

847
00:47:31,615 --> 00:47:34,157
because there was actually less...

848
00:47:34,757 --> 00:47:36,139
kind of contact area between the two.

849
00:47:36,159 --> 00:47:37,840
So we thought, if they're rougher, it'll work.

850
00:47:37,860 --> 00:47:38,501
But actually, what happened?

851
00:47:38,521 --> 00:47:40,222
They just bounced off each other even more.

852
00:47:40,823 --> 00:47:43,606
So then we had to go to plan C, which was the thing we

853
00:47:43,666 --> 00:47:45,768
really didn't want to have to do, which was this.

854
00:47:48,288 --> 00:47:55,296
So this is a rubberized spray coating which gets sprayed onto all of our hero pieces.

855
00:47:55,336 --> 00:48:00,060
It doesn't get sprayed onto all of the pieces, but so it gives it this lovely tactile kind

856
00:48:00,100 --> 00:48:04,545
of premium feel and it also makes that kind of stackability really work.

857
00:48:05,566 --> 00:48:08,108
This added about 10 percent.

858
00:48:08,909 --> 00:48:13,351
to the overall cost of our product, which is bad.

859
00:48:15,092 --> 00:48:20,934
And where we were was basically, like, this is what game design looks like if you're manufacturing.

860
00:48:21,374 --> 00:48:26,517
There is this dance happening between your product team, which is one place, your manufacturing

861
00:48:26,557 --> 00:48:28,417
team and your sourcing team, which is another place.

862
00:48:28,878 --> 00:48:30,718
You're having a ton of Skype conversations.

863
00:48:30,819 --> 00:48:33,700
You're FedExing prototypes backwards and forwards.

864
00:48:34,100 --> 00:48:35,040
You're making videos.

865
00:48:35,080 --> 00:48:37,581
You're kind of doing the, you're just figuring out how to test stuff.

866
00:48:37,982 --> 00:48:42,483
and you're trying to relate all of that back to a kind of creator's idea about what you

867
00:48:42,523 --> 00:48:45,884
want your experience to be when somebody gets this and unpacks it.

868
00:48:46,584 --> 00:48:49,905
In our case, we were also having that conversation with investors because we were also saying,

869
00:48:50,325 --> 00:48:52,046
yeah, so all of our estimates were off.

870
00:48:52,766 --> 00:48:55,907
Actually, we kind of allowed for a margin of error, but our margin of error wasn't enough,

871
00:48:56,147 --> 00:49:00,048
so we were kind of actually only about 5% over, but that was still bad.

872
00:49:01,629 --> 00:49:04,170
Now that is my idea of fun.

873
00:49:07,392 --> 00:49:13,336
So I would not recommend it if that sounds like stressful, but the dance, the relationship

874
00:49:13,496 --> 00:49:17,299
between this supply chain and all of these incredible people, like I've met so many

875
00:49:17,339 --> 00:49:23,103
amazing makers in China, and the kind of skill and the insight and the experience that they

876
00:49:23,143 --> 00:49:28,086
brought to this process was really a kind of humbling thing to interact with.

877
00:49:29,007 --> 00:49:30,928
And we got it, and it worked.

878
00:49:30,948 --> 00:49:31,469
So basically...

879
00:49:32,600 --> 00:49:37,973
The end of that story is you have to take the hit on your margin because there's no

880
00:49:38,013 --> 00:49:39,637
point in shipping a product that people don't enjoy.

881
00:49:40,568 --> 00:49:40,708
Right?

882
00:49:40,908 --> 00:49:45,413
You know, and ultimately there are a bunch of ways you might be able to solve that problem

883
00:49:45,473 --> 00:49:46,193
down the line.

884
00:49:47,054 --> 00:49:50,838
For example, changing from ABS to PVC is our kind of underlying material.

885
00:49:51,619 --> 00:49:55,903
But we can only do that if we've generated enough commercial interest to redo the tooling

886
00:49:55,943 --> 00:49:58,065
and all these kinds of, all these sort of nested things.

887
00:49:58,145 --> 00:50:02,129
But it's possible, but what you can't do is ever get back from, this product sucks,

888
00:50:02,149 --> 00:50:03,610
you can't stack the pieces, it's no fun.

889
00:50:03,891 --> 00:50:05,332
So that's where we ended up.

890
00:50:07,031 --> 00:50:13,813
So what we were surprised by was that Kickstarter drove interest not just from consumers, but

891
00:50:13,853 --> 00:50:15,753
also from commercial partners like retailers.

892
00:50:16,253 --> 00:50:21,314
So we had a bunch of emails pretty early in the campaign saying, you know, this is really

893
00:50:21,534 --> 00:50:24,075
cool, we want to stock it, will you come and show us a prototype?

894
00:50:24,475 --> 00:50:27,216
And those translated into purchase orders that meant we could

895
00:50:27,936 --> 00:50:31,317
basically triple the amount that we made in that first run.

896
00:50:32,238 --> 00:50:34,678
So cash flow and financing is another thing

897
00:50:34,698 --> 00:50:36,139
that you have to kind of get into.

898
00:50:37,559 --> 00:50:39,860
It's hard, but not impossible to do that

899
00:50:39,880 --> 00:50:42,461
if you have a purchase order from a reputable retailer.

900
00:50:43,181 --> 00:50:44,542
What you can't do is go to a bank and say,

901
00:50:44,622 --> 00:50:46,643
hey, this new product that we've never made before,

902
00:50:46,663 --> 00:50:47,323
I reckon I can sell 10,000.

903
00:50:47,943 --> 00:50:48,923
Will you give me some money, please?

904
00:50:49,424 --> 00:50:50,004
I did try that.

905
00:50:50,164 --> 00:50:50,664
It doesn't work.

906
00:50:50,804 --> 00:50:51,925
And we're just like, no.

907
00:50:53,746 --> 00:50:54,746
So that was the great thing.

908
00:50:54,866 --> 00:50:58,409
So Marbles, also a brilliant company in lots of ways,

909
00:50:58,769 --> 00:51:00,330
gave us all of this great in-store presence.

910
00:51:00,830 --> 00:51:02,692
All of that work we'd done taking the game

911
00:51:02,732 --> 00:51:03,933
to exhibitions and festivals,

912
00:51:03,973 --> 00:51:05,334
so it turned out to be super useful

913
00:51:05,394 --> 00:51:08,155
in boiling down what the demo experience was in retail.

914
00:51:08,516 --> 00:51:10,597
So it turns out there to be a very close analog

915
00:51:10,657 --> 00:51:13,339
between what happens when you walk into a specialist retail

916
00:51:13,379 --> 00:51:15,400
in terms of how they get into and understand your game

917
00:51:15,420 --> 00:51:16,521
and what happens at a conference.

918
00:51:17,433 --> 00:51:23,195
The bad part was that you need to be aware that if you're working with small scale retailers like Marbles,

919
00:51:24,155 --> 00:51:26,155
the fortunes of those companies can go down as well as up.

920
00:51:26,395 --> 00:51:30,877
They went bankrupt a couple of weeks ago and we're currently in the middle of a whole bunch of bankruptcy court stuff with them.

921
00:51:31,357 --> 00:51:36,078
So another good reason for working with Amazon as a partner is, I am pretty sure, don't quote me,

922
00:51:36,098 --> 00:51:39,879
but I'm pretty sure that Amazon is not going to go bust any time soon.

923
00:51:39,899 --> 00:51:43,019
So I super recommend working with those guys for that reason.

924
00:51:45,061 --> 00:51:47,966
If you get to this point that we've got to, so where we've now sold the game,

925
00:51:47,986 --> 00:51:51,471
we're doing more deals with retailers, we've just come back from the New York Toy Fair,

926
00:51:51,511 --> 00:51:55,578
it's all super exciting, you're then going to kind of come up against an interesting thing

927
00:51:55,618 --> 00:51:58,502
which is different between digital indie and physical indie.

928
00:51:59,749 --> 00:52:04,192
This is a quote from a CEO of a similar company.

929
00:52:04,232 --> 00:52:06,093
She's about three years ahead of where we are.

930
00:52:06,774 --> 00:52:08,715
So she's my kind of go-to person for wisdom.

931
00:52:09,475 --> 00:52:11,857
And this was really challenging when she said this to me.

932
00:52:12,577 --> 00:52:14,698
